<br>
Many zones have some VERY powerful mobs at the appropriate level that can be dire charmed and used to take down much higher mobs. SOE, for example, provided PoP zones with mobs that con green to us higher-level players but that hit like trucks (harder than many warriors) when sent into action. Grabbing a PoV dire-charmable pet and buffing it with SoV, Bedlam, and Umbra, I can contribute more than significant dps to my group (and keep myself awake if we happen to have a shammy in my group to do the slowing).<br>
<br>
The problem is, dire-charmed pets tend to misbehave. Although rarely, they can depop for seemingly no reason. Trying to get them to follow me to a camp can be a big headache. They sometimes will wander off on their own--aggroing mobs (due to bad pathing?) and bringing a horde of nasties back with them and getting me killed. I've had DC pets that have all-the-the-sudden disappeared and died--which is never a good sign. That's when I try to brace myself and my group for incoming disaster. Yes...my pet has caused a few wipes that were never fully explained.<br>
<br>
Over time I've learned to be patient and to figure out the best routes to take to safely get a DC pet to PoV camps. The last few times I've tried, I've been able to get them to the NE and HoH camps without incident. It's still a big pain though. My question: has anyone found easier ways to work with DC?Summon Companion is a joke...if it worked properly, I could DC a pet, Guard Here, then summon it at camp--it's never worked though. Another idea I've thought of is the Suspended Minion AA's. Has anyone ever successfully suspended a DC pet then summoned it at camp? I have my doubts that it would work except with the standard chanter pet. But I hope...<br>
<br>
Anyway, any other ideas welcome.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#102960><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub169.ezboard.com/bmtboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=eliasmt>EliasMT</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.aol.americangreetings.com/greetingcard/cardgifs/icons/3004487i.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Looting Highpass</span><br>  Posts: 109<br> <font color=#628CBC>(2/4/03 12:37:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub169.ezboard.com/fmtboardsfrm22.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=52.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Dire Charming...solutions?</span><hr size=1> Well even tho DC is nice, I would say its the charm for &quot;lazy enchs&quot; (not like I havent used it often myself heh) If you don't have to afk like most of the time to watch your pet, its much better to use a normal charmed pet. The difference in DPS is hundrets of DPS better on the normal charmed pet. Its nice to have a dire charmed pet that hits for 150hp's until you meet a mob that is dispelling or realize that your normal charmed pet is hitting 700+ in certain zones... Of course breaks are kinda risk, thats why I hardly ever hasted such pets, since they usually turned me into a pile of crap if I didnt watch out on break... So usually I charm a mob, put on the absorbers I can use (SoA, Uproar, Arcane Rune), sending it on the inc mobs as soon as MA picks one , nuking (unless I have to slow heh) and while waiting on recast on nuke I have my pet targeted with my finger on charm <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Its handy to TAB your pet (target pet, hit TAB, when ever you later target yourself and hit TAB it brings up what ever you TAB'ed this way, works on any targets)<br>
